## 3. Federal vs. State Jurisdiction on Abortion

### 3.1 Federal Role

Historically, the federal government has played a role in abortion through Supreme Court rulings and funding policies. For example:

- The *Roe v. Wade* decision federally protected abortion rights.
- Federal funding for family planning clinics indirectly supports abortion services ([Packwood, 1971](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/5146964/)).
- Medicaid covers abortion in some states under Title XIX ([Contis & Hern, 1971](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1529840/)).

### 3.2 State Role

Post-*Dobbs*, states have primary authority to regulate abortion, leading to a patchwork of laws:

| State Action | Description | Impact |
|--------------|-------------|--------|
| Restrictive Laws | Some states ban abortion after 6 weeks or impose strict regulations. | Limits access, especially for low-income women ([Nash et al., 2020](https://www.guttmacher.org/article/2020/12/state-policy-trends-2020-reproductive-health-and-rights-year-no-other)). |
| Protective Laws | Other states protect and expand abortion access, including allowing advanced practice clinicians to provide abortions. | Maintains or improves access to reproductive health services. |
| Legal Ambiguity | Some states have conflicting laws or pending litigation. | Creates uncertainty and uneven access. |

### 3.3 Debate Over Jurisdiction

Some argue abortion should be a federal issue due to its fundamental human rights implications, while others emphasize states' rights and local governance ([Harold, 2014](https://rationalabolitionist.blogspot.com/2014/04/why-abortion-is-federal-issue-and-should.html)).

